Net Sec Challenge

Target IP: 10.10.255.176
Challenge Description: Practice the skills you have learned in the Network Security module.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.255.176 -p- shows there are six TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. I will need to perform an aggressive port scan to identify the services on the different ports.

I performed an aggressive port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.255.176 -p 22,80,139,445,8080,10021 against the six TCP ports and obtained the result shown above. By the looks of it, there are a range of different applications: HTTP, SMB, FTP, SSH, etc. Time to answer the questions of this challenge.

Questions & Flags

  1. What is the highest port number being open less than 10,000?
    From the previous port scan, the answer is 8080 and it seems to be running a Node.Js web application.

  2. There is an open port outside the common 1000 ports; it is above 10,000. What is it?
    The answer is 10021 and it seems to be running FTP on this port.

  3. How many TCP ports are open?
    From previous port scan, a total of six TCP ports were open on the target machine.

  4. What is the flag hidden in the HTTP server header?

    To obtain the flag, I used curl and the mode -I to only obtain the HTTP server header. The command I used is curl http://10.10.255.176 -I. The flag is shown above.

  5. What is the flag hidden in the SSH server header?

    The SSH server header contains the flag shown above. I used the command nc -v 10.10.255.176 22 to grab the server banner.

  6. We have an FTP server listening on a nonstandard port. What is the version of the FTP server?
    The FTP is running on port 10021 according to the port scan during the reconnaissance phase. The version of the FTP server is vsftpd 3.0.3.

  7. We learned two usernames using social engineering: eddie and quinn. What is the flag hidden in one of these two account files and accessible via FTP?

    On my machine, I created a file with the name usernames. Inside this file, I inserted the two usernames: eddie and quinn. Then using hydra and the command hydra -L usernames -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.255.176 ftp -s 10021 I performed a bruteforce attack against the FTP application on port 10021. I successfully bruteforced the password of both users, as shown above.


    Then I connected to the FTP application on port 10021 using the credentials quinn:andrea and obtained the flag shown above. The command I used is ftp 10.10.255.176 10021 to connect to the FTP application on the higher port.

  8. Browsing to http://10.10.255.176:8080 displays a small challenge that will give you a flag once you solve it. What is the flag?

    The webpage above is displayed for this web application on port 8080. It informs me to perform a port scan covertly against the target machine without being detected by the IDS. Let's begin!


    Bingo! Using the command sudo nmap -sN 10.10.255.176 -g 80, I was able to covertly port scan the target machine without triggering the IDS as shown above. The flag is shown above too. Overall this task was super simple and fun to complete :)
